6 cm with good neck extension.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features is most predictive of difficult bag-valve-mask ventilation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Presence of facial hair","History of hypertension","Thyromental distance of 6 cm","Age 62 years","Mallampati class II"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests the ability to distinguish between predictors of difficult intubation and difficult bag-valve-mask ventilation, which are distinct clinical entities with different risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresence of facial hair\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the strongest predictors of difficult mask ventilation as it prevents an adequate seal between the face mask and the patient\u0027s face. Along with obesity and lack of teeth (both present in this patient), facial hair forms part of the \u0027MOANS\u0027 assessment for predicting difficult mask ventilation (Mask seal, Obesity/obstruction, Age \u0026gt;55, No teeth, Stiff lungs).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistory of hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary predictor of difficult mask ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyromental distance\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to predict difficult intubation. A distance less than 6 cm suggests difficult intubation, but this measurement has little bearing on the ability to achieve adequate mask ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge 62 years\u003C/strong\u003E, while part of the MOANS assessment (Age \u0026gt;55), is a relatively weak predictor compared to the presence of facial hair, obesity, or edentulous state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMallampati class II\u003C/strong\u003E is a measure of the visibility of posterior pharyngeal structures and primarily predicts difficult intubation rather than difficult mask ventilation. A class II score (where the soft palate, uvula, and tonsillar pillars are visible) is considered reassuring for intubation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient has multiple risk factors for difficult mask ventilation (facial hair, obesity, and lack of teeth), highlighting the importance of careful airway assessment and preparation before anaesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mallampati score and thyromental distance primarily predict difficult intubation rather than difficult mask ventilation.","Presence of facial hair, body mass index \u003E30 kg/m\u00b2, and lack of teeth are key predictors of difficult mask ventilation.","MOANS mnemonic (Mask seal, Obesity/obstruction, Age \u003E55, No teeth, Stiff lungs) helps predict difficult mask ventilation."],"references":["Bucher JT, Vashisht R, Ladd M, et al. Bag-Valve-Mask Ventilation. [Updated 2023 May 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441924/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62649"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18726"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62649"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T10:07:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T10:08:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11458"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77143"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://a